fn.p:
One way to determine Kendall's τ correlation coefficient of two series X, Y of real numbers is to compare positions of observed pairs of (Xi
,Xj
) and (Yi
,Yj
) with their positions if X and Y are rank ordered. If the order of positions remains the same, no move is required to transform these parts of X and Y into each other. Otherwise, the order of either (Xi
,Xj
) or (Yi
,Yj
) must be reversed for matching, equivalent to one move of an element. (The direction of move is indicated by the sign of −1 or +1.) Kendall's τ is the fraction of all moves actually required to transform the ranks of X and Y into each other in the number of moves possible at maximum. It ranges from −1 to 1 with 1 indicating perfect correlation and 0 indicating perfect disorder. Kendall's τ is valid even if no linear relationship between X and Y exists and if the values of X and Y are not normally distributed.
